SIMPLE: evacuate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Evacuate
<hw>E*vac"u*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Evacuated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Evacuating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[l.
<ets>evacuatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>evacuare</ets> to empty, nullify;
<ets>e</ets> out + <ets>vacuus</ets> empty, <ets>vacare</ets> to be
empty. See <er>Vacate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make empty; to
empty out; to remove the contents of; <as>as, to <ex>evacuate</ex> a
vessel or dish</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: To make empty; to deprive.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Evacuate</qex> the Scriptures of their most important
meaning.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To remove; to eject; to void; to discharge, as the
contents of a vessel, or of the bowels.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To withdraw from; to quit; to retire from; as,
soldiers from a country, city, or fortress.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Norwegians were forced to <qex>evacuate</qex> the country.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To make void; to nullify; to vacate; <as>as, to
<ex>evacuate</ex> a contract or marriage</as>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Evacuate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Evacuate
<hw>E*vac"u*ate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To let
blood</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Burton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>to expel stool from the bowels; to
defecate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>evacuated</ent>⟦br⟧
